# Cursor Rules for Reactr Playground

## Project Purpose & Structure

**Reactr** is a platform that enables creators to monetize their content through interactive offerings where supporters can request custom content reactions, covers, and more. This project is a **demo showcase platform** for static UI/UX experiences of the Reactr platform - we build and showcase different interface variations without database connections or network calls.

## Reactr Platform Overview

### Core Entities
- **Creators**: Content creators who set up offerings and fulfill requests
- **Supporters**: Fans who purchase offerings and make content requests
- **Offerings**: Configurable products (content requests, polls, Q&A, suggestions, live queues)
- **Requests**: Individual supporter submissions with content links/details
- **Groups**: Segmented supporter access with different pricing/limits

### Offering Types
- **Content Requests**: Supporters submit YouTube/Spotify/IMDb links, creators fulfill with reactions/covers
- **Polls & Voting**: Interactive polls for community engagement
- **Q&A Sessions**: Live question and answer interactions
- **Suggestions**: Community-driven content ideas
- **Live Stream Queues**: Interactive request queues during live streams

### Platform Features
- **Multi-Channel Integration**: Patreon, Twitch, YouTube, Discord
- **Dynamic Configuration**: Custom pricing, limits, visibility per offering
- **Supporter Groups**: Tier-based access with override capabilities
- **Content Parsing**: Automatic metadata extraction from submitted links
- **Live Interactions**: Real-time queue management and community engagement

### Domain Terminology (Use in Demos)
- **Offerings** (not "products" or "services")
- **Requests** (not "orders" or "purchases")
- **Supporters** (not "customers" or "users")
- **Fulfillment** (when creators complete requests)
- **Tiers** (Patreon/Twitch subscription levels)
- **Concurrent Requests** (multiple active requests at once)
- **Request Limits** (per-user or per-offering restrictions)

### Demo Organization
- **Landing Page**: Directory of all demo groups (`src/app/page.tsx`)
- **Demo Groups**: Organized by user type (e.g., `creator/`, `admin/`, `user/`)
- **Feature Folders**: Group related demos by feature (e.g., `dashboard/`, `profile/`, `settings/`)
- **Demo Iterations**: Numbered demos within each feature (e.g., `demo1/`, `demo2/`, `demo3/`)
- **Static Only**: No API calls, no database - pure static experiences with mock data

### URL Structure
```
/{group}/{feature}/demo{n}
/creator/dashboard/demo1  # Creator dashboard variation 1
/creator/dashboard/demo2  # Creator dashboard variation 2
/admin/settings/demo1     # Admin settings variation 1
/user/profile/demo1       # User profile variation 1
```

### Adding New Demos
1. **Create Group**: `mkdir src/app/{group}` (e.g., `src/app/creator/`)
2. **Create Feature**: `mkdir src/app/{group}/{feature}` (e.g., `src/app/creator/dashboard/`)
3. **Add Demo**: `mkdir src/app/{group}/{feature}/demo{n}` and create `page.tsx`
4. **Update Landing**: Add entry to demo groups array in `src/app/page.tsx`
5. **Group Related**: Use same feature folder for variations of the same experience

### Demo Best Practices
- Use realistic mock data that represents actual use cases
- Include multiple states (loading, empty, error, success)
- Demonstrate interactions and animations
- Keep demos focused on specific experiences/features
- Use the component library for consistency
- Always add new demos to the landing page directory (`src/app/page.tsx`)
- Group related demos by feature (dashboard, profile, settings, etc.)
- Use numbered demo folders (demo1, demo2, demo3...) for iterations
- Each demo should represent a variation of the same experience

### Demo Categories to Create
- **Creator Dashboard**: Offering management, analytics, request fulfillment
- **Supporter Portal**: Browse offerings, submit requests, view history
- **Live Stream Tools**: Interactive queues, real-time engagement
- **Admin Settings**: Offering configuration, supporter group management
- **Content Parsing**: Link submission and metadata display
- **Payment Integration**: Tier selection, pricing displays

## Component Library Structure

This project has a well-organized component library in `src/app/lib/` that should be used for all UI interactions. Always prefer existing components over creating new ones.

### 📁 Library Structure

```
src/app/lib/
├── elements/           # Basic UI building blocks
└── theme/             # Theme management
```

## 🎯 Elements (Basic UI Components)

Use these for basic interactions and UI building blocks. Import from `@/lib/elements`:

### Core Components
```tsx
import { Button, Avatar, Badge, Link, Logo } from '@/lib/elements'

// Primary button
<Button>Click me</Button>

// Outlined button
<Button outline>Secondary</Button>

// Danger button
<Button danger>Delete</Button>

// Avatar with image
<Avatar src="/avatar.jpg" alt="User" />

// Status badge
<Badge color="green">Active</Badge>
```

### Form Components
```tsx
import { Input, Textarea, Checkbox, Select, Switch } from '@/lib/elements'

// Text input
<Input placeholder="Enter text..." />

// Textarea
<Textarea rows={4} placeholder="Enter description..." />

// Checkbox
<Checkbox label="Agree to terms" />

// Select dropdown
<Select>
  <option>Option 1</option>
  <option>Option 2</option>
</Select>
```

### Layout Components
```tsx
import { SidebarLayout, StackedLayout, AuthLayout } from '@/lib/elements'

// Sidebar layout
<SidebarLayout>
  <Sidebar>Navigation</Sidebar>
  <main>Main content</main>
</SidebarLayout>

// Stacked layout
<StackedLayout>
  <div>Header content</div>
  <div>Main content</div>
  <div>Footer content</div>
</StackedLayout>
```

### Data Display
```tsx
import { Table, Pagination, DescriptionList } from '@/lib/elements'

// Table
<Table>
  <TableHead>
    <TableRow>
      <TableHeader>Name</TableHeader>
      <TableHeader>Email</TableHeader>
    </TableRow>
  </TableHead>
  <TableBody>
    <TableRow>
      <TableCell>John Doe</TableCell>
      <TableCell>john@example.com</TableCell>
    </TableRow>
  </TableBody>
</Table>

// Pagination
<Pagination>
  <PaginationPrevious href="/page/1" />
  <PaginationPage href="/page/2" current />
  <PaginationNext href="/page/3" />
</Pagination>
```

### Overlays & Dialogs
```tsx
import { Dialog, Alert, Tooltip } from '@/lib/elements'

// Modal dialog
<Dialog>
  <DialogTrigger>Open Dialog</DialogTrigger>
  <DialogContent>
    <DialogHeader>
      <DialogTitle>Dialog Title</DialogTitle>
      <DialogDescription>Description here</DialogDescription>
    </DialogHeader>
    <DialogFooter>
      <Button>Close</Button>
    </DialogFooter>
  </DialogContent>
</Dialog>

// Tooltip
<Tooltip>
  <TooltipTrigger>Hover me</TooltipTrigger>
  <TooltipContent>Tooltip content</TooltipContent>
</Tooltip>
```

## 🧩 Components (Complex Features)

Use these for specific features. Import from `@/lib/components`:

### Animation Components
```tsx
import { AnimatedCollapse, FadeIn } from '@/lib/components'

// Animated collapse
<AnimatedCollapse isOpen={isOpen}>
  <div>Collapsible content</div>
</AnimatedCollapse>

// Fade in animation
<FadeIn>
  <div>Content that fades in</div>
</FadeIn>
```

### Drawer Components
```tsx
import { DrawerBase } from '@/lib/components'

// Base drawer
<DrawerBase open={isOpen} onClose={() => setIsOpen(false)}>
  <div>Drawer content</div>
</DrawerBase>
```

### Form Components
```tsx
import { HandleInput, QuilEditor } from '@/lib/components'

// Handle input (for social handles)
<HandleInput platform="twitter" />

// Rich text editor
<QuilEditor value={content} onChange={setContent} />
```

### Search Components
```tsx
import { UniversalSearchButton, UniversalSearchOverlay } from '@/lib/components'

// Search button
<UniversalSearchButton onClick={openSearch} />

// Search overlay
<UniversalSearchOverlay isOpen={searchOpen} onClose={closeSearch} />
```

### Loading States
```tsx
import { ProfileShimmer, ImageShimmer } from '@/lib/components'

// Profile loading skeleton
<ProfileShimmer />

// Image loading placeholder
<ImageShimmer />
```

## 🎨 Theme Management

```tsx
import { ThemeProvider, ThemeToggle } from '@/lib/theme'

// Wrap app with theme provider
<ThemeProvider>
  <App />
</ThemeProvider>

// Theme toggle button
<ThemeToggle />
```

## 📝 Development Guidelines

### ✅ DO:
- Always import components from `@/lib/elements` or `@/lib/components`
- Use existing components for common UI patterns
- Check if a component already exists before creating new ones
- Follow the established naming conventions
- Use the theme system for consistent styling

### ❌ DON'T:
- Create new button/input components - use the ones from elements
- Duplicate existing functionality
- Style components from scratch when library components exist
- Ignore the established design system

### 🔍 When to Create New Components

Only create new components when:
- No existing component meets the specific requirements
- The functionality is truly unique to this project
- You've checked all existing components in the library
- The new component follows the established patterns

### 📚 Component Categories

**Elements** = Basic building blocks (buttons, inputs, layout)
**Components** = Feature-specific implementations (search, drawers, forms)

Always start with Elements for basic UI, then use Components for complex features.

## 🚀 Quick Start

```tsx
// 1. Import what you need
import { Button, Input, Dialog } from '@/lib/elements'

// 2. Use existing components
function MyComponent() {
  return (
    <div>
      <Button onClick={() => console.log('clicked')}>Click me</Button>
      <Input placeholder="Type here" />
    </div>
  )
}
```

This ensures consistency, maintainability, and follows the established design system.
